		<marginalia book_id="FolgersHa2" hand="Italian" id="Ha2.141r_0001" marginalia_continues_to="Ha2.140v_0001" marginalia_to_transcription="Ha2.140v.xml">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ille noster in dicendo, agendoq[ue] grauiss[im]a semper expeditus,
						et laetus: etiam in Tragicùs Co[micus]. Totus mu[n]dus no[n] dignus tristi = [[G4v]: = vultu: nedum Corde ferenti a[e]grè, id est, sordidè, et miserè.
						Nam vulgares isti, pla[e]runq[ue] ignobiles, sordidi, miserabil[e]s.]
						<!-- Continues on facing page, right margin, Ha2.140v -->
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Our man there is most ready and cheerful in saying and doing the most serious things;
				even in a tragedy, he is comic. The entire world is not worthy of a sad [[G4v]: face: still less hardly of bearing a heart; that is, in a foul and wretched manner.
				For those men are vulgar, and many of them are ignoble, foul, and wretched.
				But He remains ever lively, even while most afflicted by troubles.]
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
